      <h4 style="text-align:center">Rural eMentoring</h4>
      <% case @level %>
      <% when 0.1 %>
        <h4 style="text-align:center">Introduction</h4>
        <h5>0.1 – Welcome!</h5>
        <p>Welcome to Rural eMentoring BC, or ReMBC, for short. This program matches you with a mentor who is a current post-secondary student. Your mentor could be anywhere in the province and attending any of the various programs offered at their school. Before we start, let’s look at these two words:</p>

        <div style="text-align:center">
        &#x2192; MENTOR (noun)<br>
        An experienced and trusted adviser or guide.<br>
        <br>
        &#x2192; MENTORING (verb)<br>
        To be a trusted advisor or guide to another person.<br>
        </div>

        <p>You will be working with your mentor for the duration of the program and they will help guide you through different topics and questions in this curriculum. This is your Personal Quest – it is your chance to ask questions about what you are interested in, explore different possibilities for after graduation, and to also find out more about what your mentor is doing and what their experiences have been.</p>

        <div style="text-align:center">
          <div style="text-align:left;display:inline-block;border:1px solid black"><div style="float:left"><a class="pop"><img src="/assets/custom/ubc/dr-adams.jpg"></a></div><div><p>“If you want the best out of life, you have to give your best. It's hard work. Follow your heart. Tell yourself you're going for it. Do it with courage, kindness and community mindedness.”</p><p>Dr. Evan Adams<br>Canadian medical doctor, actor, playwright, Chief Medical Officer for the First Nations Health Authority and member of the Tla'amin First Nation.</p><p>Read more here! <a href="https://www.viu.ca/news/aboriginal-students-learn-about-opportunities-malaspina" target="_blank">https://www.viu.ca/news/aboriginal-students-learn-about-opportunities-malaspina</a></p></div></div>
        </div><div style="clear:both"></div>

        <p>At the end of each activity there will be questions for you to discuss with your mentor.</p>
        <p>These discussions can go back and forth and include new questions that you are interested in knowing more about.  Don’t be shy!</p>

        <ul style="font-weight: 700; font-style: italic">
          <li>Have you ever had a mentor before or have you ever mentored before? What was it like?</li>
          <li>Are there any particular interests or goals you would like to explore?</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Once you have finished this activity, click below to learn more about Communicating on MentorCity.</p>
      <% when 0.2 %>
        <h4 style="text-align:center">Introduction</h4>
        <h5>0.2 – Communicating on MentorCity</h5>

        <h6>Communicating Online</h6>

        <p>The majority of your communication with your mentor will take place within the Personal Quest. Areas with bolded and italicized text indicate that it is a section for you to discuss with your mentor. These sections are easy to find because there is a text box following these sections.</p>

        <div style="border:1px solid black;margin:20px;padding:10px;background:#ccbbcc;font-weight:700">
          <h6>*IMPORTANT*</h6>

          <p>When discussing things with your mentor please do not share personal information like your last name, personal email, or phone number. This includes social media contact information such as Instagram, Twitter, Facebook, Snapchat etc. Communication with your mentor should only take place through the MentorCity platform or organized through your teacher and the ReMBC team. If you are unsure what content may or may not be appropriate to share, please ask your teacher first.</p>
        </div>

        <p>You and your mentor can share thoughts and ideas in the Quest without other people like friends and family seeing what you type. The only people who can see what you type are:
        <ul>
        <li>your mentor</li>
        <li>your teacher</li>
        <li>the eMentoring staff</li>
        </ul>
        </p>

        <h6>Netiquette</h6>

        <p>Remember to use good internet manners (called “internet etiquette” or netiquette) any time you post to the discussion with your mentor (and other social networking websites too).</p>

        <div style="padding:4px;border:1px solid black;text-align:center;overflow:hidden">
          <p>Digital Etiquette (video)<br>
          <a href="https://www.brainpop.com/technology/digitalcitizenship/digitaletiquette/" target="_blank">https://www.brainpop.com/technology/digitalcitizenship/digitaletiquette/</a></p>
        </div>

        <p>Do the Digital Etiquette POPQuiz! (Do the review quiz version).<br>
        <a href="https://www.brainpop.com/technology/computersandinternet/digitaletiquette/quiz/" target="_blank">https://www.brainpop.com/technology/computersandinternet/digitaletiquette/quiz/</a></p>

        <p>Whenever you are on-line, stay safe and think about who will be able to see what you are sharing. Not everything is private and many things you post becomes part of your digital tattoo (also called your digital footprint).</p>

        <p>Want a break? Play the game Stop that Post (<a href="http://www.nsteens.org/Games/StopThatPost" target="_blank">http://www.nsteens.org/Games/StopThatPost</a>) on NSTeens.org, a website of NetSmartz Workshop.</p>

        <ul style="font-weight: 700; font-style: italic">
          <li>Have you ever broken any netiquette rules? Have you ever experienced bad netiquette?</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Once you have finished this activity, click below to learn more about your Mentor.</p>
